Issues.Body:
This PR implements scenario-based persistent component state restoration to support enhanced page navigations, allowing developers to declaratively control when state should be restored based on specific scenarios.

## Problem

Currently, persistent component state only works during the initial render of components for a given runtime. This creates issues for enhanced navigation scenarios where:

- Components show stale data briefly before fetching fresh data (flickering)
- Components unnecessarily re-fetch data that could be provided via state
- Developers have no clean way to opt-in/out of state updates per scenario
- Behavior is unpredictable - developers can't control when components receive state updates

## Solution

This implementation provides a layered API that allows developers to specify per-property when state should be restored based on the restoration scenario (prerendering, enhanced navigation, server reconnection).

### Core Infrastructure

- **`IPersistentComponentStateScenario`**: Extensible marker interface for restoration scenarios with `IsRecurring` property
- **`IPersistentStateFilter`**: Interface for declarative filtering logic 
- **`RestoringComponentStateSubscription`**: IDisposable subscription for restoration callbacks

### Web-Specific Components

- **`WebPersistenceReason`**: Enum with flags for `Prerendering`, `EnhancedNavigation`, and `Reconnection`
- **`WebPersistenceContext`**: Concrete scenario implementation with render mode support

### Declarative Filter Attributes

- **`UpdateStateOnEnhancedNavigationAttribute`**: Restores state only during enhanced navigation
- **`RestoreStateOnPrerenderingAttribute`**: Restores state only during prerendering
- **`RestoreStateOnReconnectionAttribute`**: Restores state only after server reconnection

All attributes include render mode compatibility checks to ensure they only apply in appropriate contexts.

### Enhanced State Management

- **`PersistentComponentState`**: Added scenario-aware restoration with `RegisterOnRestoring()` and `UpdateExistingState()`
- **`ComponentStatePersistenceManager`**: Added `RestoreStateAsync(store, scenario)` overload
- **Value Provider**: Enhanced with automatic scenario filtering using reflection

## Usage Examples

### Data Grid (receives updated state on navigation)
```razor
@inject PersistentComponentState AppState

<table>
    @if (forecasts != null)
    {
        @foreach (var forecast in forecasts)
        {
            <tr><td>@forecast.Date</td><td>@forecast.TemperatureC</td></tr>
        }
    }
</table>

@code {
    [SupplyParameterFromPersistentComponentState]
    [UpdateStateOnEnhancedNavigation]
    public WeatherForecast[]? forecasts { get; set; }
}
```

### Form (preserves user input, doesn't receive new state)
```razor
@inject PersistentComponentState AppState

<EditForm Model="model">
    <InputText @bind-Value="model.Name" />
    <InputText @bind-Value="model.Email" />
</EditForm>

@code {
    [SupplyParameterFromPersistentComponentState]
    [RestoreStateOnPrerendering] // Only restore on prerendering, not navigation
    public ContactModel model { get; set; } = new();
}
```

### Imperative API
```csharp
protected override void OnInitialized()
{
    AppState.RegisterOnRestoring(WebPersistenceContext.EnhancedNavigation, () =>
    {
        if (AppState.TryTakeFromJson<WeatherForecast[]>("weather-data", out var data))
        {
            forecasts = data;
            StateHasChanged();
        }
    });
}
```

## Implementation Details

- **Backward Compatibility**: All existing APIs continue to work unchanged
- **Extensible Design**: New scenarios can be added by implementing `IPersistentComponentStateScenario`
- **Performance**: Minimal overhead - filtering only occurs when scenarios are active
- **Safety**: State can only be updated when the existing state dictionary is empty (fully consumed)

## Testing

- Comprehensive unit tests covering all new functionality
- Tests verify scenario creation, equality, filtering logic, and attribute behavior
- All tests pass and maintain existing functionality

Fixes #51584.

